## Why include a cell-level proposal head at all?

Because without it, pair candidate selection has only bad options:

```text
Option 1:
  score all legal pairs exhaustively every time

Option 2:
  sample pairs mostly randomly

Option 3:
  rely only on terminal tactical rules

Option 4:
  use a pair scorer only on a weak hand-built candidate set
```

None of those is the strongest design.

The reports are clear that the model should not be pair-only. They recommend a single-cell proposal head because it gives dense supervision through pair marginals, tactical saliency, and reusable proposal structure; pair-only learning is too sparse. 

That does **not** mean the final policy is single-cell. It means the model has a dense auxiliary/proposal view over legal cells so the pair candidate generator is not blind.

In the final model:

```text
cell_marginal_logits != action policy
cell_marginal_logits == proposal/marginal/auxiliary head
```

The actual searched action remains:

```text
unordered pair {a,b}
```

---

## Why include a conditional completion head?

Same reason: candidate generation.

A pure joint pair scorer can score candidate rows, but it does not by itself tell you which rows to create unless you either enumerate all pairs or have a retrieval mechanism. The reports recommend autoregressive/factored proposal specifically because it avoids the quadratic action explosion while keeping pair actions as the search-semantic object. 

But the final plan should define this carefully:

```text
pair_completion_logits(anchor=a, candidate=b)
```

not:

```text
policy_pair_second(first_move=a, second_move=b)
```

The head is an **anchor-conditioned proposal function**, not a statement that the game is sequential.

Training should use both unordered views:

```text
pair {a,b} creates:
  completion target b | anchor a
  completion target a | anchor b
```

The latest plan already has the right idea that conditional targets must not train only the canonical first cell, because that leaks row-order artifacts. 

