## Add direct pair retrieval

This is the biggest improvement I would make to the candidate-selection plan.

The candidate selector should not be only:

```text
cell marginal -> anchor -> conditional completion
```

It should also use the new model’s pair interaction structure directly.

For example, the model can produce legal-cell embeddings:

```text
h_i
```

Then produce low-rank proposal vectors:

```text
u_i = W_u h_i
v_i = W_v h_i
```

and a cheap symmetric pair proposal score:

```text
s_prop(i,j) =
  0.5 * (u_i · v_j + u_j · v_i)
  + cheap_pair_features(i,j)
```

Then retrieve top candidate pairs from this score matrix.

This does **not** mean materializing pair tokens in the graph encoder. The plan already correctly rejects pair actions as attention tokens because pair rows should reference legal token vectors rather than inflating the token sequence. 

It also does **not** mean exhaustive pair MCTS. It means the model may use efficient pair scoring/retrieval to choose candidates, and then MCTS searches only the admitted subset.

So the source list should become:

```text
direct_pair_retrieval:
  candidate pairs from cheap symmetric low-rank pair proposal score.

anchor_completion:
  candidate pairs from cell_marginal anchors plus conditional completions.

cell_marginal_cross:
  unordered pairs from top marginal cells, mainly for stability/debug.

terminal_exact_v1:
  protected immediate win/block pairs.

structured_diversity:
  legal-row / geometry / distance / window coverage diversity.

blind_canary:
  tiny diagnostic source.
```

This is stronger than relying on `policy_pair_first` and `policy_place`.

