## Does the plan broadly match the research report intent?

Yes, broadly. The core thesis matches very well.

The reports say the best path is not full exhaustive pair MCTS and not fully sequential search. They recommend unordered joint-pair search after the opening, with factorized/autoregressive proposal inside candidate generation, Gumbel-style root admission, progressive widening, candidate-aware targets, and a symmetric pair reranker. 

The final plan says the same main thing: post-opening MCTS action is an unordered pair; full exhaustive pair enumeration is rejected; sequential afterstate search is a baseline, not the main planner; pair rows are canonical and D6-validated; pair outputs cannot control runtime by head-name presence; and unsampled legal pairs are unknown, not negatives. 

The plan also correctly adopts the report’s model direction: graph/set encoder over legal cells and windows, not fixed crop and not pair tokens. 

So the broad plan is right.

But the plan needs three clarifications to fully match your intended “completely new best model” framing.

